column1: I am doing this project to become a better teacher
That teaching, from K-12 summer campis to college /courses to professional development workforce trainings, involves IA Ethics in moreorless explicit ways
Teaching of the sort that I do involves instilling habits of mind and frank moral clarity on a bundle of related AI Ethics questions, cases, and concerns
In large part, scholarly endeavors on AI Ethics and its education have pertained to enumerating principles and certain best practices, an approach taken in emulation of bioethics
But I am not convined that such a narrow, practice-focused or rule-focused approach alone will adequately prepare my students for the real world, its changes, and their place in it
[Brief: missing acounts point]
As I urrently see it, AI practitioners include [...]
In light of recent and ongoing cases and costly infrastructural decisions, we want to carry out these facets in ethical ways
The outcomes, understandings, and processes of one’s ethical AI work are shaped by a number of lived, hard-to-disentangle aspects, such as [...]
[Brief: these are narratives, and narratives not understood]

Understanding these aspects as well as practice-and rule-focusedviews will enable me and those in similar positions to ensure that our students are aware of AI ethics issues, aware of values held by others that warrant respect, aware of the completeness or incompleteness of views held by oneself and others and traced in the skills necessary for ethical AI work
Moreover, students will be equipped with narrative points of comparison when carrying out AI ethics practices and when reflecting on one’s place in the ever-accelerating social change around AI
Kahanna
Don’t let your feelings sabatage your success (Ru).
Find the thing that gives you joy and share it (Jimbo)
What future doe you see for your students?
Ask that, unpack as I go, and ask pragmatic questions.
Lunch.random
It felt hard to not have an introduction to give for myself.
I study AI ethics, and right now I’m asking about what futures teachers see for their students today.

Why does tht matter? 


I’m filling in the cracks.
Well, to a large extent, the AI Ethics literature has centered on listing some set of principles
That’s fine and all, but folks take for granted that that style of thought comes from principlciplist bioethics, which has its own history that goes back thousands of years

AI Ethics doesn’t have a history even remotely close to that, so we’re missing some of the narrative and case example touchstones that are required for thinking through principles and weighing how they apply in real life practice

So I come in, someone with a background in AI, memoir, creative nonfiction, and a few other things and I’m asking folks about the futures they see for their students, because I find that that ggives us a bit of material for unpacking, seeing what values and worries they hold, and catching the scent of the narrative touchstones that AI Ethics people actually do have in mind, but we haven’t done a lot of work to put on paper and connect to the rest of the project.
There’s popular examples, like Propublica and Pasco, but the real life application of principles demands a lot more
Useful examples are often mundane, and between Propublica and Pasco examples and others, we don’t have much variety
So you’re looking for stories?
And those stories turn the participants’ values?
And if students hear this, they’ll be better at ethics?
How do you know that that will work?

The first is I’m making this assumption that there are people out there doing good AI Ethics work, their work is consistent with principlist approaches, and that good principlist approaches require these rich histories of narrative touchstones
It’s like the literary imagination that people bring to understanding any case at hand
So by assuming all that, I also have to assume that theose rich histories already eist
AI isn’t happening in a bubble; there’s a millenia of human thought behind it
Right, second, Katie Shilton did some empirical work a while back thta found that software engineers are more likely to think about ethics when they can take cases personally
So by telling students these narratives, by broadnening their imagation of the world, my hope is that they’ll better be able to empathize
Do you mean putting themselves in others’ shoes?
When I work with students, I find that they have all these worries about the world
Putting themselves in others’ shoes isn’t really the issue
It’s that AI is scary and the world is changing and it’s hard to see themselves as having any place in it
Slomeone called this just giving up and going and being a cog in the machine
You want to make it feel...real to them, is that it?
You could have picked anything, why this topic?
That’s difficult
I think, because, it’s the question that I wish someone would tell me the answer to, and a question I feel gnawing at me---what’s the future hold, what place do I hold in it?
Yeah, but it doesn’t actually need an answer, I don’t think
My favorite classes in college were memoir and creative nonfiction
And those classes don’t provide answers.
They just...feel
And as an ethicist, I findm I go a lot further quicker by just asking how I feel about something and unpacking that
There’s more to it than that, obviously, but it’s so impoertant for a project that I find I spend 99% of my time just doing that
Etverything else is procedural, it follows
And that’s what your’re doing here, feeling?
And when you students can’t feel---
Right, when the cases isn’t real to them, that’s 1% of the effort trying to give 100% of the answer.
For you at least.
This project here is just about those futures that teachers are seeing for their students and wherever unpacking that goes
This is just the reason that interests me more
A story well told
We didn’t know what we were doing
We were afraid of what was coming
It, was confusing
We tried to hide that fact, apply what we had done before to this new situation
Something about this situation was new
Maybe we had seen it before, but never like that
Working at the university, we saw it in the students
Tiredness
Grasping for hope
A tool, a way out
It was not new for them
An inevitable next step in a resistance against everything we had tried to teach them
Permission---we never gave them permission to be, anything but what ChatGPT could be
The narrowed existence we’ve asked them to be
It’s not about narratives
It’s about permission to be more than narrow
Fewer questions
More examples
When they make a box, have them look at the box, ask if it’s really there.
Why is that important?---Ask why we don’t see ___?---ask of the things they want to get at
Cut narrative interpretation, cut collarboation, keep the car.
Asking these things, I put all the issues on the table.
Creative nonfiction.
FG---what could we have them look at that would shine light on ___?
They got into AI without formal training, with a non-CS degree
They used AI to help solve physics problems
They started working for a company outside their academic domain and learned the domain through immersion, “learning something about the subject matter was extremely helpful”
They contrast the industry as boring with the technology they are bringing to the picture, “otherwise very boring and stodgy world of insurance” vs. “very cool tools to solve some important problems”

They contrast work that they characterize as hard with the potential of the technology they are bringing to the picture, “insurance documents, which kind of are almost their own language and a language that a lot of people have a hard time parsing” vs. LLMs and “how can we use that to be able to, for example, build question answering systems that solve issues for them”
They see media literacy as important in the face of misinformation
Misinformation is easier now than in the past to propagate and to generate
Advanced mathematics knowledge is valuable when learning about AI only in limited cases
In contrast, having knowledge in basic statistics, familiarity with state-of-the-art AI techniques, and familiarity with AI techniques in vogue---these are very useful
Basic software engineering skills are important for industry roles

Basic software engineering skills are often overlooked as important even when they are, “easily overlooked in preparation for industry roles, and it’s one that shouldn’t be overlooked. It’s actually super foundational, being able to understand” how to install Python, understand basic computer architecture, Unix commands, and Docker
Even as AI continues to advance, it will be important for its practitioners to have skills in basic computation, math, stats, internet, and data, as these will continue to underly AI systems

They appear to equate the position of AI vogue advancements with problems to be solved and their solutions, in the way that both will continue to evolve, “What’s the most important problem to be solving today and how do we solve it? I think that’s gonna change faster and faster.”
They seem to contrast their narrative against some unstated normal narrative.
They tinkered with programming as a kid on compute devices at home.
But they did not like the languages they were taught, C and Java.
They learned Python, outside of college it appears, and were relieved by it, and it seems their relationship with programming changed due to that.
They contrast their narrative with an imagined “bolt of lightning” narrative where they would have been immediately comfortable with programming.
Instead, it appears to be important to their narrative that they came to that comfortability slowly and through a constellation of different exposures.
They also appear to not have gone straight from formal education in programming straight to a profession in programming, but instead to have had hobby projects along the way, I assume in Python.
When learning computing, struggling through and finding solutions, especially crude initial ones, benefits you in a number of ways.
You appreciate your solution more.
You appreciate others’ solutions more.
Coming to a solution feels refreshing.
It is a more vivid learning experience.
It is conducive of long-term retention.
You develop habits out of cautionary experiences.
You learn to frame new struggles as learning opportunities and appreciate them.
They hedge about ethics being broad and a lot of people have thought about it
They contrast that hedging with direct practical advice to become familiar with real examples of cases where AI has failed

They see a tendency in those failures to occur where practitioners are uninformed, “blind spots,” or negligent, “nobody really pausing, taking a breath and asking questions that are really kind of obvious”
There are numerous and growing numbers of examples of AI failures
AI encodes human biases and unfair practices and beliefs
AI reinforces human biases and unfair practices and beliefs, because it scales up human effects on other humans
Being aware of real AI failures inoculates you against being uninformed and negligent

Practitioners need to be vigilant and have a spidey sense to reflect whether one’s AI approach is right, by some sense of right, and of various AI aspects, such as data, collection, and target measures
Technology represents a promise to scale up, quickly and to huge effect
With great power must come great responsibility
They seem to recount a view held by imagined others that the law is just politics
They contrast the law-is-politics view with a view that responds to that imagined other, giving an account of law that shows how it is valuable even for and especially for practitioners
This contrasting view is that law is an articulation of ethics that reads like a program
Law codifies cases, eliminates cases, and identifies edge cases. In this way, it mirrors a habit of mind that practitioners understand and value in problem solving
They parallel that stance of law with AI development, as in both we have to reckon with different articulations of ethical concepts, such as discrimination

Law-as-articulation is practically valuable to practitioners doing AI work because it articulates ways to reckon with discrimination and balance a range of concerns; in any case, AI practitioners will have to do this, because AI is based on data and metrics
[Disparate treatment vs. Disparate impact]
Practitioners need to be vigilant because morally-charged decisions are infrequent compared to any other decision made in the normal course of business
The targets of models, forecasts, and predictions aren’t usually morally-charged
It can be hard to spot issues that are infrequent
Practitioners need to (a) be able to spot that they are facing a morally-charged decision and (b) be able to make the right decision

“The frequency that you in a day job are actually exposed to fraught decisions is actually quite rare. It is not a day-to-day occurrence, and if anything, that’s what makes that sort of hazardous....These sorts of things are failures that can be easily caught, but they do require a little bit of vigilance....Though the pitfalls appear infrequently, that’s all the more reason to be that much more vigilant, because it can be challenging to, it’s challenging to spot things that come infrequently.”
Insurance companies and their consumers are aligned in their aims, even if that is not the press they often receive
Insurance companies are motivated to align with consumers and to act in ethical ways, in part due to heavy regulation and public trust
Being a good developer involves quantitative elements, such as creating models with appropriate loss functions, trained and tested appropriately, and evaluated more highly than their predecessors
Maybe change “good developer” to “good practitioner”?
Being a good developer involves [Hora: Communication and documentation]

Being a good developer involves reflectivity and asking questions that guide one’s work, such as value added to one’s consumers; how a product makes life better, helps communities, and helps achieve goals; and potential positive and negative impacts of one’s work
One should be vigilant across the efforts in these aspects of the practice, ie., quantitative, communicative, and reflective
[Outsized Impact]
[90% of AI work is just software work]
[Most of AI work is just data munging]

The major events that have shaped AI’s trajectory so far involve improvements in hardware and physical computing; the commodification of storage and computing at scale via cloud computing; and shared benchmark datasets for model evaluation, such as ImageNet
Cloud computing is more than a resource, it is a symbol that figures in practitioners’ problem-solving process

For example, when one’s local machine has inadequate storage or compute capability, one may ask, how important is it to solve this problem at all, and if it is important, how might we scale it in the cloud, and what amounts of resources and what kinds would we need?
I did not ask about roles in driving the car in this one
The future of AI will be driven, as it has been, in large part by collaborations or mixed efforts between industry and academia and those doing fundamental research
Companies are less beholden to peer review than academia
AI, unlike other fields, has a larger proportion of its advancement owed to industry instead of academia

Learners should work on projects that are interesting to them, as interesting projects can drive one’s real internal motivation; at the same time, interest in projects can be fleeting, so one should also use initial motivations to develop habits and disciplines that can carry one’s interest and activities further.

“Pursu[e] something where you have interest and you can take motivation, which is something that can be really powerful, … but also fleeting, and it just, it will dissipate and you can lose your motivation in a week, or in a day, or in an hour. But if you can take that motivation and channel it into the discipline of a habit...you can harness the power of habit, you’ll go a lot further than if you just sort of try and run, surf the wave of motivation as far as it can go, because it won’t take as far”
Learners should learn Python, specific Python libraries like numpy and pandas, and learners should experiment with Kaggle datasets and challenges
This participant provides two perspectives I haven’t had before and hadn’t considered: someone laid off in recent nationwide layoffs in tech, and someone who has done a lot of work in strategy
Computing professions today are facing nationwide layoffs
The future of AI will continue to have issues related to bias, discrimination, copyright infringement, and privacy
Moreover, the current trend suggests an increase in issues related to IP infringement and job displacement

They got into leadership by being there when a there was a vacuum that needed to be filled for someone with technical knowledge to help guide organization strategy and goals from below, “It’s very easy to find places where they know they want to do AI, but there’s not any institutional know-how about it”
[Like 0707], they appear to imagine their narrative in contrast to some imagined, unstated norm

Where AI differs from software at scale in general is, (1) existing companies with legacy products and processes underestimate the efforts necessary to integrate AI into their portfolio, such as the new teams that will need to be created, new reporting structures, new collaborations between teams, and new experience imagining products that use AI; (2) non-AI software at scale design requirements are old hat, as companies have long histories of defining them, estimating their efforts, and estimating their resources; in contrast, AI design requirements are currently more amorphous and require much more iteration and exploratory thinking to get right; (3) and companies are turning to AI in part due to the fear of missing out, which arises in part from AI’s outsized potential and promise, yet unclear future of what the next game changing AI product will be
The risk of AI failures is greater when AI practitioners are isolated from those with domain knowledge, and do not have domain knowledge themselves
AI tempts practitioners into habits of not understanding one’s domain or business context
Peer review structures, done well, can help mitigate this problem

“I've worked with data scientists...who quite very explicitly said, ‘I don't need to understand the business because I can just use XG boost, which is a really powerful machine learning model, and I can just throw the data at it and it will come up with a good model.’ And on paper it does, but in practice it’s nonsense, and...it’s not useful or misleading in some not-obvious way”

AI models made without domain knowledge can harm the company in a number of ways, even when deployed for short periods of time, such as (1) executives making incorrect decisions and (2) customers being impacted at enormous rates

“If you get one of these models wrong, the executives might make devasting decisions...or you make a model that’s doing real-time predictions about all your customers, and it’s predicting stuff about 1000 customers per second, and if you have the wrong thing in product for an hour, you could really hose your business.... You could just see on the charts for the business that everything tanks like that very second.”
Framing AI issues in terms of risk can help communicate them to business executives
Risk is a broad term that includes ethical, financial, and legal concerns
AI, like all software at scale, should be designed from business purpose and problem towards one’s solution, not the other way around
Practitioners do have an interest in having an impact on the business
However, [Pilot, have to be willing to engage with humanities side of thing]

Practitioners will have a better job experience as a result, because the hard work they put into what they create will more likely lead to business impacts; otherwise, they run the risk of putting a lot of work into something that will not matter
The tooling around AI has improved, so being familiar with that tooling is just one expectation from employers, among also [Hora, communication and collaboration, more likely to hire]
This view is common in industry
This timeline question doesn’t seem to be getting me anything outside what I already have in literature review
It doesn’t seem to be getting at the sense of social change that I wanted
Same with Good Developer and aspiration
Perhaps I should reword that question to, What is it that good developers want to get right, why?
Several times in its history, what has been considered im/possible to do with AI has changed
Moreover, where AI applications will go or find success has been hard to predict
[Lit review, Winning chess, AI winter, “AI” being a dirty word, nn rebirth]

A turning point for AI development was a move from attempting to model how humans reason in applied situations, to what computers are good at: performing lots of complex calculations on fast hardware.
[0707, Mixed efforts of industry and academia]
[Job displacement]
[Encoded bias, proxies for protected attributes]
AI applications are increasingly able to predict human behavior, which raises moral questions in a range of fields, such as insurance and policing
An important turning point in the future of AI will be whether open source and academic AI applications will be able to compete with large industry actors who currently hold outsized power
In this, there is ongoing research in the ability to make larger models computable on smaller, cheaper compute devices, such as one’s own laptop
In the past, advancement in AI models was made in distinct fields of applications, such as vision and natural language
Today, there is a growing trend toward models that are effective at a range of tasks and that operate on a range of modalities, such as ChatGPT
“You don’t make money betting against AI”

AI practitioners, in a company just getting into AI, can have outsized influence on the direction of AI in their company if they (1) are able to help leadership set priorities, (2) are willing to grapple with uncertainty in messy problems, (3) understand what is/n’t possible with AI applications, (4) can establish collaborations between technical and non-technical teams, and (5) can translate between technical teams and stakeholders
Because the tooling around AI is improving, people can get into it without a formal technical background by, for example, reading blogs and watching YouTube videos
So in turn, professors and classes that teach introductory programming and AI libraries, and merely teach them in a lecture-heavy way, are less valuable to students
However, students will be better prepared for their future practice if class time is spent collaborating with other students on messy problems
For learners, [0707, The struggle is instructive], and teachers should consider [0707, Kaggle examples] and GitHub repos, having students imagine what is possible of it

This, among other possible things, helps students learn how to come up with their own problems, restate them, make them more precise, [0707, wrangle with data], and [Hora, learn basic tech competence]
[Pilot, inherent value of discussion]
[Hora, employers like to see evidence that students have Years Off the Farm grit]

It is necessary to the benefit of the business that practitioners be able to communicate even when dealing with messy problems and to be able to redefine those messy problems, to get at underlying concerns, facts, and solutions

They seem to be imagining bad experiences and responding to that, like bad hires that have annoyed them, and bad teaching experiences they’ve had, heard about, or project onto education; in any or any combination of cases, they seem to be talking here in a cautionary sense
I wish I had asked more about what seemed to be behind these words
Modern AI architecture has moved away from its early attempts at mirroring how humans reason, including neural networks, which were named in reference to the human brain
Still, however, this metaphor has stuck, and we see AI spoken about in the zeitgeist and in some research as though it were more human-like than it really is
[Ullman, in our image]
Repeatedly in AI’s history, there has been skepticism about what its capabilities could be
While this skepticism was warranted, each time in the end it turned out to be false

“This group that I worked on at ((lab)) we did theorem proving, and they had made the decision long before I got there that they couldn't care less how human mathematicians proved theorems, they were going to do it by brute force using heuristics, kind of like how we play chess with 


computer and...it just works. But that would have been considered crazy, was considered crazy, for quite a long time before the 


number of successes just reached the point where it's impossible to deny”
Perhaps this skepticism is rooted in hubris that there is something special about the human brain
Chess and art, once thought to be impossible to reduce to computation, are both now, in some way or another, run of the mill examples of AI
It appears trivial
Commonly, people forget, or speak as though they forget, that AI has been continuously surprising
The ethical issues that arise are not the ethical issues that were expected
The job displacements were not the displacements that were expected
I don’t buy this completely. I wonder who the “they” is he is imagining. My sense is that the iSchool has been ringing the bells for some time

Still, humility is required when dealing with AI Ethics; it is too easy to claim, in retrospect, that we saw where AI’s trajectory was headed, when repeatedly we’ve been wrong, so to say otherwise would be unfair to the reality of the situation
[Alan, story about Snowden]

Subject Matter, Isolation, and Designing for Purpose: problems arise when practitioners lack subject matter, domain, and business knowedge; when they are isolated from those who do; and when they design systems out of FOMO and from the solution position first, instead of from the problem or business purpose first.
Without these aspects, practitioners crerate systems that are misaligned with the real use context.
Adding Value and Real Internal Motivations: Practitioners do want to add value to their company, their users, their communities, and so on
This is a real internal motivation, and achieving it goes a long ways toward making one’s job feel fulfilling

At the same time, one can feel at odds with certain moral stances or framings; one may see themselves as incapable of humanities-style thinking, and so they disengage with certain parts of that real internal motivation to have positive impacts
The Promise of IA and its Skepticism: The history of AI has been lined with outlandish, extravagant promises, and skepticism about its limits
The skeptcis repeatedly have been shown wrong; and the prommise today acts as a symbol in its own right in media
AI’s hype and amorphousness relates to this
Moreover, it serves as a tense aspiration, to achieve great things that live up to the promises of AI, whiele at the same tie not fakling prey to its speciousness
We can turn our nose up at the young upstarts buying into the hype, while at the same time being jealous of them

Foundational Skills of the Profession; Building Beyond the Foundational Skills; and the “Right Vita” Narrative of its tTensions: Competent practitioners need a baseline set of foundational technical and engineering skills
They also need a set of communication, reasoning, industriousness, and other “soft skills” that are grown in humanties classes and by struggling with real world, messy problems
At the same time, there is an industry narrative about how one gets into tech positions, a “right” narrative that is imgrained and against which other narratives are judged
Which are worth more? Which are real? Which are legitimate?
The non-traditional routes, however, are good for building one’s subject knowledge and those “soft skills.”

Risk, Responsibilitiy, and Best Intentions: Practitioners seem to frame their ethical stances from a first position of risk and a deeply held sense of responsibility as a member of the profession to mitigate those risks---even if the particular risk is little-understood or unarticulated
For example, the ML+X tlak

Moreover, practitioners seem to have a sense of responsibility that overrides any sense of “best intentions”; this phrase, “best intentions,” seems to factor into their assessments of others who have fallen short of that responsiblity

Stakes and Scales: AI Ethics matterse, and it matters with a sense of urgency, because the stakes to consumers, business, and other stakeholders is high; and the scale of AI in production can lead to devasting impacts, even when the system is deployed for a short time.
Industry, Open Source, and Aacdemic Landscape: Unlike other deomains, advancements in AI involve a larger proportion of Industry efforts in comparison to Academic efforts
Moreover, a few industry actors hold an outsized position to deply AI applications
A turning point in the future of AI will be the ability of small scale compute resources to run powerful models, as this will bolster competition from academia, open source, and smaller start-ups
The Symbols and Function of Critical Thinking
Real Alignment and Bad Press
Translating to Leadership
Organizational Barriers
Temptation and the Human Metaphor
Let Computers do What Computers are Good at
Falling Infrastructure, Tooling, and Learning Barriers
Surprised and Unclear Horizons
Write everything down as far as I can see
[[wrote 12 pages, 46 more to go --- note, that is an over-estimate of work left, since those pages have doodles that will not be transcribed]]
I started doing this because that’s the way I saw Burke doing it---in Motives, he’d start each section with a section header, which were the idea the section started with, notm where it was headed
His writing would go wherever he wanted it to go.
The Dramatist Hexad was a compact way to remember questions one might ask of a subject of one’s inquiry.
To mine all one might know about  a thing, pick a question, and follow it where it takes you
That exhausted, pick another.
“Need anything?” [sitting at Java Cat]
“I’’m good---thank you”
There is a woman here who sounds exactly like Dorothea
It’s not her, an older, elderly woman, talking with two of her friends.
A quiet morning.
Sunbeam on my table.
Music plays, the speaker just up and to my right, the corner near the back door.
My Alarm goes off for my morning estradiol.
A breakv to eay my quesadilla.
Told Dorothea on mastodon her doppelganger-but-just-in-voice is here.
Alarm went off again---bit. I didn’t repack my meds last night for the week, so I have to go back home soon, instead of sitting at Java Cat all morning.
Such a bummer.
Give the feeling a voice---I won’t be able to work on my dissertation now
This really takes the wind out of my sails
I’’m kicking myself for not refilling my meds last night that was stupid
Break to drink my london fog.
I tell Megan about the bummer.
They message me back a voice message
An idea, of us sitting together in a cafe, us both doing business on our laptops, sipping coffee, they’re just playing video games
I can do this.
Morrison
My alarm goes off. My headphones are in. There’s tones in the alarm I’ve never heard before. It’s nice.
Morrison also writes about mining
It’s a different sense---mining a shared language for the words to say it
For Burke, it’s about minig one’s attention by directing it to diffrent areas

Lammott’s one-inch picture frame gets at both; there’s more loe in that one, tbhan Burke; it reads like advice (“on writing and life”) thgan the hexad; she’s standing over you, like Burke, unlike Morrison, whose attention is elsewhere.
It’s comforting.
One-inch picture frame
A list.
I came up with a list. Last entry, november 6.
I wanted to write down all the things I was seeing. ---Important, methodologically, but---I felt like I was trying to write down that I did see, was seeing something.
I had self-doubt unresolvved that my interviews were coming up with anything and that I had anything interesting to say, a RQ at all.
This is the same feeling I had all summer, and the year before then---doubts that I was getting at anything.
So yeah, there’s a list. There’s something good in the list. Recording the list is important for posterity.
Alarm. Undertones.
The question seems to be, how do practitioners do their job, how do they do it right; and not from a methodologicaly, “what they do with their hands” perspective, but a question of how they be.
Not-dorothea gets up to leave. She tosses her stuff away. She looks at me. We smile. Wisconsin nice.

“How they be,” I mean more than professionally, motivtionally, aspirationally, practically, dispositionally, emotionally, positionality, situatedness, beliefes, habits;---but I mean real internal sense.

column1: [bundle of issues: existential threat, growing scope of application, bias, IP, misinformation, job displacement, professional shifts]
[Job displacement]
The participant was careful to separate “ethics” from the broad sense, ie., a discourse in literature and in the zeitgeist about a bundle of related issues pertaining to data and automation at scale
Instead, they made a point to define ethics as a study of morals and obligations
AI Ethics is capacious
One may find themselves interested in a range of issues
Related as those issues may be, what facets one will find most instructive about moral theory and about AI technology will turn on the specific issue in question
One should, at the least, come equipped with a broad understanding of different moral theoretical stances
[previous interview, Ethical issues are rare in day to day, may not appear to come up]

The work of AI practitioners in a position may not be limited to the mission of their employer, as the employer or team may take on additional work for stakeholders outside that mission in order to keep their bills paid
The ethical questions that arise, or one’s perception of them, may hinge on who the extra work is for and what tasks the work involves
There is joy in wrangling with hard philosophical and engineering puzzles
[below, what one learns in these puzzles can shape their moral views in subsequent situations]

The participant holds the view that there is no one right moral theoretical stance in AI ethics, though there may be those that profess to follow one right stance or instruct others as though the stance they are teaching is the only right one
Instead, the participant holds that one needs a foundation in a broad range of views, as this better allows one to understand AI ethics debates and to understand one’s own views

“I do think it's important for people making decisions to be sort of careful and reflective, but I'm not somebody who thinks like you should just like go learn the true moral theory and then follow that because I don't think there is one.”
Good AI developer involves at least two facets: being good in the skills of one’s job description, and being a good person

“It's sort of acting trying to like fit standards of ethical behavior, making sure to, like, whatever exactly that means, making sure to make decisions that like promote human welfare and don't harm anyone.”
[connect to literature in philosophy about difference senses of good, and/or on an ecumenical stance that seems to get at what these participants care about]
These senses of good can conflict with one another.

In the course of carrying out one’s job duties [note, one’s skills is separate from what one is asked to do with those skills], one can be asked to do tasks that powerfully conflict with one’s own moral views

“And I should also acknowledge that like these different senses of good come in tension with each other, like for example, if I'm designing my chat bot or voice bot software and like I want it to like perform well, one thing that we measure a lot is like can it keep like the person calling, can I keep it within its system rather than transferring to a live agent? And so like we employ all kinds of interesting tricks to keep keep the human talking to the chat bot or their voice bot, rather than having them get transferred to a live agent, so the more of those checks I can perform like the better I do in my job in some sense, like the more money we get. But also like it causes the humans they're talking to these chat bots and voice bots some amount of stress or pain as they're like desperately trying to talk to human, and we're like, ‘Are you sure you don't wanna talk to me? I'm really like great and like if you talk to human like we might have to charge you money for doing the same things you can do when you talk to me’ and so on. So yeah, there's a fair bit of tension.”

“I think this was also true of...my previous job, where we're willing to take on various interesting contracts because like they company need to stay afloat....Part of the reason I left that job and came to my present job was uh, we started working on technology related to like oil drilling and like trying to...guide oil drilling in the best way possible. And I guess like being a liberal type person and I was not a big fan of oil drilling. And so there like, performing well at my job and sort of following what I think of as ethical guidelines came apart, I guess sufficiently much that, like, it helped drive me to quit.”
Just because moral issues are paid attention to, by practitioners or fields of practice, those issues are not automatically any easier to solve.

Even if there is not one “right” moral stance for AI practitioners, there may still be patterns in what real practitioners do when trying to be “right” that may be instructive and may moreorless be consistent with one another.

Getting at one’s moral aims in AI practice can be hindered by (a) lack of time to spend reflecting on or thinking deeply about moral and technical problems before decisions need to be made; (b) one’s sense of self-worth and tendencies to shy away from ethical reflection; (c) the wide range of domains of expertise one may need to be familiar with in order to contribute meaningfully to moral issues that arise, and how rare it is for one to possess such a range; and (d) a lack in prompting in one’s day to day work that bring moral reflection to one’s attention.
[ch 2, the part on ethnography and what we’ve learned so far]
Such prompting may have been impacted by the pandemic and the move to remote work in recent years.

Moreover, (e) one may be chilled in exploring AI ethics issues more deeply in their place of work, or speaking out about those issues, because of how previous employees were treated when they went deeper or spoke out

Still, even when one’s ability to get at their moral aims in AI practice are hindered by one factor or another, they may still hold real internal motivations that affect what they do or how they think about their place in their work.

“If you think carefully about what's going on with AI research and work, there are like potentially very bad things that are happening and people don't like to think of themselves as contributing to bad things.”
The participant came to philosophy by following interesting question after question after being exposed to philosophy at a young age.

Although they painted their high school and college days as days where they reflected often on what they wanted to do with their lives, ultimately their first job in tech was chosen because it was located in the same city as their spouse
They paint this type of choice as “random,” contrasting it to jobs chosen in the field in which one trained
[personal story, I had the job talk for tiny earth the day after this interview]
The participant works with coworkers who have a range of trajectories
Some are traditional, having gone to school for Computer Science or having taken Computer Science courses

Others, like themself, got into their job by following job postings for tech jobs on non-tech job boards, going where their friends were, and so on, ending up in companies with an existing amount of academic diversity.

They paint such factors that motivate the nontraditional employees as “randomness,” as though such factors are unrelated to the work of the job itself: location, compatibility with family plans, social networks, market availability, and so on.
Some companies have a mix of their own employees working alongside employees managed by venders
This can increase the diversity of backgrounds one encounters in one’s work, as well as create tiers of which employees are [I got the sense from their comments] are more or less legitimate
[Good teaching reinforces [Hora skills], independent at least in part of the subject matter of the course itself.]
Good teachers can teach a range of subject matter, because teaching itself is a distinct skill.

The participant’s views, as they see it, were shaped more by the puzzles they found interesting in their academic and professional career and the time they spent working on them; and less by particular, powerful events

The moral puzzles, “they’re actually quite gripping for me personally because like I don’t know how to work out this solution to them, and I feel like it’s very important too. So, it’s kind of stressful [in a good way], those kinds of puzzles.”
It took them searching their mind—for something they had recently brought up—to recall a formative event, namely their quitting a job on moral grounds
This moral objection would be no different if AI was involved or not; it was the project’s end use that they objected to, not the particular means
[Future driven by economy]

The people who are doing cutting edge research and development on AI may not be as driven by profit motivations as others; they may be driven to some degree more by solving the hard problems themselves.
The direction that technology is headed is affected by the technology decisions that came before it, so one can steer the direction of technology by how they shape technology today

Moreover, funding and strategy can direct what kinds of technology are explored, so those in positions to affect funding and strategy decisions can shape technology at a broader, almost market-like scale
Still, the participant is skeptical that everyday practitioners will have the range of expertise necessary (let alone the opportunity) to steer the future of AI in substantive ways

Bad press is not the only signal of where technology is headed and the light that will be shined on it; technology can also alleviate stressful job conditions and make certain types of engagements newly possible or accessible.
Some participants remarked on my use of metaphors in framing otherwise abstract questions
“I thank you for using a car metaphor for it rather than a sports metaphor. I would not have understood this metaphor.”

Here, the participant was able to understand the salient features of the metaphor and how they worked together to construct a complex question, even though neither of us were experts in the subject matter of the metaphor itself: We both “get” how cars work and move well enough to understand that there are several forces that operate on a vehicle, only some of those forces being in human control, and there being a vague sense of the direction the car is headed in
[connect to literature on metaphors, reason, mental models, thinking through abstract things, …]
[Simon, car, driving in fog metaphor]
I find it interesting that the participant framed the unknowability of the future of AI not in terms that we cannot know the future, but in terms that we aren’t conscious of where the car is headed
In a way, their language seems to suggest that we are, in part, just not awake to it, that maybe there are implications of AI that we can foresee but aren’t considering
Good teaching reinforces [Hora skills], independent at least in part of the subject matter of the course itself.
AI Ethics courses cover interesting materials
Some students take them because they are interested in the questions that will be explored in the course
AI Ethics courses can also be requirements for Computer Science degrees; even in that case, AI Ethics courses can pose interesting puzzles to the students that will get them engaged
One way to do this is to engage them in topics that relate to their own lives
[2020 pilot, choosing topics that students are interested in, video game ethics]
[Shilton, seeing one’s own data as a moment where one reflects]
And when a few students are engaged, other students may pick up on that and become more engaged too
This teacher let the students vote to choose what topics they’d be interested in
Students should be encouraged to follow what interests them; it can point them towards what they want to learn more about
[2020 pilot, students not shying away from humanities style problems because they view themselves as tech people.]
Even so, humans are not as narrow as they may make themselves out to be, and one can find interests in a surprising range of subject areas outside their own academic or professional home

“I think humans are like, even if they tell themselves they're taking a course, represent particular reason or taking a job for a particular reason, they're broad, complex creatures. And like you can find ways to engage them.”
[Perhaps link this to the traditional/nontraditional path thing?]

AI Ethics is capacious; learners and practitioners should be humble, as it requires a wide range of mastery, it covers a wide range of subject area knowledge and facts on the ground, and the technology in question is always evolving.
The literature on AI Ethics is capacious

Even when one is motivated to inform themselves on AI Ethics subject matter, it can be discouraging to encounter (1) the sheer amount and range of material on AI Ethics, and (2) the variety in quality in what one reads
This participant described a lot of AI Ethics writing as arrogant and terrible
These discouraging factors can make it more difficult for one to become competent in scholarly views on AI Ethics
All right, first real video memo.
So I just got done going through and tabling up some notes on the second two interviews.
That's interview 84 O one and one O 9 three and then going through printing out the two tables, not the whole transcripts 'cause that would be almost 200 pages of transcript.
So I've got about 20 pages here of tables that I've been going through with the color pencil and annotating and looking for common themes between just these two interviews.

I'm not letting myself draw connections kind of between these interviews and the previous ones just yet, because I don't want to run into an anchor bias where the first two interviews that I looked at structure too much of the findings that I'm noting in the future ones, right?
So I'm being careful to kind of keep moving along instead of going back to the first one over and over and over this time very different from the first two interviews.
So the first two interviews I looked at, I came away with a set of discreet themes, and I've written those down and I'll do a video kind of spelling out my thoughts on them more in a bit.
But just a set of discreet themes or in this one, it started to kind of emerge in my head was more of a graphic, right?
And so I've got this.
I'll hold this up with the camera for a second, this graphic way of representing the connections between things and how they're relating.
So I'm just going to read through this and kind of talk about it out loud.
So we've got this kind of this Venn diagram overlap thing between ethics and policy and how those connect.
For the policy side, I'm thinking right now a good strategy might be to rely on the existing literature.
Lessig is a good place to go for some of the stuff people are noting.
And then I've got that one book that I always like to cite in from my EPS studies.

But for the ethics side, something that's starting to emerge is this kind of three different ways of looking at it that I'm seeing that kind of work together and people move between these stances as they're making sense of things.
So different senses of what ethics is or what AI ethics is.
So one is kind of a bundle of related issues of you that's like, oh, we need to care about privacy, we need to care about bias, blah, blah, blah.
So are these enumeration approaches kind of related?
I guess as it come up recently, but I can imagine coming up is principles, Approaches like, oh, we need to make sure we do this or do this or do this.
But kind of those stances that are all about enumeration, any specific duties or sense of obligation, enumerated or not.
So I start to get a little bit more towards maybe a moral theory perspective of here's things that we ought to do or ought not to do in general.
And then a vaguer sense of just like this discourse that's in the zeitgeist that when I bring up AI ethics, I'm usually gesturing towards.
So this could be the literature, this could be bad press, kind of public opinion, things like that.
So one kind of triad here is this ethics and policy interacting with this hands on awareness that people get interacting with this sense of documentation.

So both of these interviewees talked a lot about the awareness that you get of ethical issues of a system that you can get sometimes only or sometimes only as deeply by actually getting hands on with the particular system that you're working in.
One of them went at length, and I've got this giant quote that's amazing that I want to drop in later about how when you're the first one to work on a system, you're more than anyone, right?
You and your team who designed it are going to think more deeply about the system than anyone ever will.
And so it's very important for you to document that thinking.
And they spell out a number of things that would fall into and make that look good or not to document that thinking so that it becomes part of the institutional knowledge.

And when you're working on systems, whether you're maintaining them or creating new ones from scratch or so on, you kind of have this professional expectation to engage with the previous documentation, to engage with the people who have thought more deeply than you, be it on the particular system you're working with or say particular guidelines that have come out of bodies like a NIST, right.

There was a big a very emphatic recommendation for people to use the particular framework from the NIST is a starting point just because it's so thorough compared to a lot, a lot of other places people might start.
And so there's a sense of documenting prior knowledge and engagement prior knowledge as a practice.

But you gain at that by being hands on that you don't gain by not being hands on, especially the people making it for the first time and then the relationship, which is the various senses of ethics and policy, right, and how all those kind of fit in.
I'm kind of point out this side right here coming down from ethics and policy down the other side there, there seems to be this scale between kind of mission driven and puzzle driven.
So I've been asking people what they think a good developer looks like and something that's repeatedly come up over and over is the well, there's two different senses of good.
When I say a good developer, there's the skills driven side of things and there's a morally good side of things.
And when I'm asking them about, well what's happening in the overlap, there are people who get at both what their aspirations might be or so on.

There's this emerging sense of, well, OK, you might what this overlap looks like might look different depending on if you're in a situation where you're more mission driven or in a situation where you're more puzzle driven, right.
And what can move you along that scales of various number of things that we can just for now call like your employment contacts, contacts, who else is being hired around you?
Is there like a disposition that people are being hired for, for where they're at along that scale?
Are you working at say a non profit or government agency that is very mission driven by design.

Are you working in place that's for profit driven And so maybe you were in a place where you don't agree with the mission, but you still are fine working there and you see yourself as a strong professional.
And so maybe what you view is less getting at this aspiration to improve healthcare, whatever and more of here's this particular engineering problem or this research question or so on.
And there's this relationship along this axis with how you engage your documentation, how you do your hands on practice, But more importantly, I think with that ethics and policy piece, right.

So when you're in a more mission driven side of things, it might be that the ethics and policy become more of a basis for taking action, kind of a positive view of things that we care about say healthcare and therefore we're going to design things to improve healthcare.
Whereas if you're on the more puzzle driven side of things, it's like OK, well here's all the things we might possibly do to solve this thing.
What are, what are the constraints that are being put on us?
A more of a negative sense of ethics and policy.
So you've got something that's more prescriptive or maybe a principal list approach of things which these two haven't brought up.
But just because principal show up so much in the literature, I wanted to kind of keep track of where I think that might fall out.

A lot of these interactions here between the employment context and all the other pieces I've mentioned before, the ethics policy hands on the documentation and so on of the barriers that might get in the way.

And the two big ones that have repeatedly come up and a few others from one of them that I've got some literature that helps spell out is do you actually have time to think about ethics and do ethical best practices?
Are those things prioritized?
Have you gotten signals from maybe higher ups that we don't really care about these things and so on.
And so they're these, they're going to be practices that get in the way, seems to be the framing of things.
Possibly because I asked the question that way, I might think about it, add an extra question kind of flipping it on what practices might help them get at it.
So I have both the positive and negative kind of cut across those lines.
The other half is getting more into a sense of self and less into a sense of practice, right?
So I've got this Top half of the drawing is more of a sense of practice, and the bottom half seems to be more of a sense of self.
So you have related to the ethics and policy part of the doodle here this various real internal motivations that people might have enumerated or aware of them or not.
This little triad relationship between your the realtor motivations that you hold, maybe various things that might chill or demotivate you in that, such as bad press.
Just the overwhelming amount of AI ethics literature at one of the participants so far has called filled with a lot of bad writing.
I need to follow up with him about this.

I mean I think he might be speaking towards like this style of writing coming out of like critical theory side of things that's a little bit more high minded and a little bit less practical, hard to follow kind of says a lot without saying anything that style of writing.

I've heard one of my friends call it like a liberal nonsense, even if you're left-leaning right, having a sense of like, well, this is maybe this is a liberal point of view, but it's written in this way that's mostly just linguistic and not grounded in in anything.

And so there might be something there that he's speaking to, but some kind of sense you get this real term motivation interacting with various things that might chill or you motivate you, the other participant has said, or maybe it was that first one, that people might be chilled by how previous employees who have wanted to go deep into ethics have been treated.
He pointed to an example that is big in the news, the Timnit, Timnit, Gebru case.
And things like that might go, oh, well, you know, I I'll still do evil for money or I'll do less good for money because I it's really important, important for me to hold this job.
And I've seen someone else who did something I aspired to be or to do get kind of really bad hurt.
And I have to make this professional, this personal call of do I still really care about that enough to put my profession in jeopardy or my current employment in jeopardy?
You know, the third part of this triad is what I just called the sense of professional being.
And within that, so far I have some notes about the trajectory that someone might be taking or how they view their trajectory.
And so all four of the participants I've talked to so far have said that they have this weird or non traditional or kind of tangential trajectory into their current role.
We've had people who said, oh, I started in physics and now I'm an AI or someone's like, Oh well, I don't see myself as a policy person, but I've kind of fallen into policy or so on.

One of the two recent participants did this interesting thing where he kind of contradicted himself, which was neat to note when I was going back and reading my table today, kind of painting all these reasons for choosing his job as random.
So he had this job that he chose after reflecting for a long time about like doing things with purpose to suddenly I'm now choosing a job because I want to go live closer to my wife or a spouse.
They might view the reasons why they take their roles for various reasons.
Even if they view themselves narrowly, we're still complex people and so you've got different people might view what counts as the real part of why they do what they do differently from other people.
So for me, I am very upfront about how an important part of the jobs that I take or that they're in Madison, because being local in Madison is important to me, whereas others might view that as well.
No, that's not the real part, right?
If I were to admit that that might maybe paint some kind of conflict on why I do what I do, who knows?
They also, everyone I've talked to has viewed their trajectory as not being something with big and important terms, but something that's the the sum of a bunch of small steps, right?
Small projects they've worked on that have tweaked their views on ethics one kind of after the other.
And so they're at just kind of the sum of where they're at.
Whereas I very explicitly come to my view on AI through the work that I did with David Shaffer's lab, which happened during my first year in HRT.
And I came to view up view my own methods by applying them to my own journal for my first year on HRT, which was mod in like these big dramatic live transitions.

And even though the participants, none of them have viewed their life in these sudden dramatic turn of ways with these kind of non linear ways as I might be mine, they still do have one or two kind of big moments.

And so it might be worth in this point here, that there are multiple ways to view what count as part of our way we see our role, that there are life transitions that we go through that are irrelevant to that, such as changing jobs or moving cities or so on, that might have some impact on how we view ourselves.
And all this matters because even if people might not view being local, whatever is part of their identity, making things feel local might nonetheless still engage them deeply with some topic.
So I wanted to do a memo just kind of reflecting on some process so far and how things have gone.
So it happens to be that just like in the 2020 pilot, when I'm going through the DO analysis, I have two interviews to analyse together, right?

Just in the time based off the timing of when I actually have time to do the analysis to listen back through the recordings or reread through transcripts or whatever and begin to generate these tables at that moment.
I've recently done two interviews that I have an interview I haven't analyzed.
So I'm analyzing them together.

And like in the 2020 pilot, that's been useful for seeing things one level of abstraction higher than one interview at a time and kind of getting some fortunate, useful things that are shared between two interviews in a way that doesn't running.
That doesn't run the risk of an anchor bias of having an interview, and my only way of moving up a tier of abstraction is to compare it to previous interviews, right?
If I'm always doing that, the first few are going to have outsize impact compared to the last one.
Having them go through in pairs kind of fortunately lets me move up layers of abstraction without that anchor risk.

And then when I'm coming to do the integrative memo across all of them, I'll begin to see the higher level things without that outsize impact of that first one, kind of affecting everything that comes after it.
Unlike the first one, I am doing my tabling.
Am I memoing differently?
So in 2020 I did my tabling and memoing on paper, all handwritten out.
A lot of them I did sitting in the courtyard in the humanities building, right?
It was just a good, quiet place that I could find to catch up on things.
Here I'm typing up digitally my tables.
I'm doing them in a little bit of a different way.
I'm also not listening to a recording that I have to pause and play repeatedly.
I can actually read through the automated transcript.
So the whole process goes like this.
I do an interview during the interview.
I turn on the automated transcript after I've gotten permission from the interviewee to do that for one of them.
So far the transcript has turned off part way through, so we didn't miss a small bit of the recording of the transcription, but we quickly noted it.
Because it's doing a live transcription, we can see those errors when they happen, so we turn on the recording.
We left the recording for the rest of the interview.
Even there was only like a a 3 minute chunk that I actually ended up being missing in the transcript.
And once it the once we got into the recording I made sure to verbalize everything that I had just heard.
So the things that were missed still made their way into the record one way or another.
And so our first pass at the transcript is really just seeing it happen live in front of us.
Me kind of mentally noting OK I see these errors going on in it or I see it pausing or cutting out or so on.
Then the next pass of the transcript is me taking that raw transcript that I've uploaded to Box and copying it into the clean folder and beginning to go through and anonymize it.

So I look for any reference to cities that stand out or particular papers they've written or very unique work they've done, employers, things like that, and replace them with double parentheses annotations.
That's like, hey, I'm changing this chunk not because I'm adding a note to it, but because I'm anonymizing it.

If I see them during the interview, if I notice that they are mentioning a particular name repeatedly, like for example, if someone worked at Yahoo and they're saying the word Yahoo several times, I can find replace that one, which is employer, right?
And I go through that.
The transcripts tend to be about 80 pages.
You know, it's kind of a narrow column worth of text, but it's still 80 pages.
And when I see other things and I'm like, Oh yeah, this is a place where the transcript is, is wrong in a way that I want to fix, right?
So it might mishear some things like UMS sometimes get turns into like OMS or OS or so on things like that.
AI sometimes becomes 2 words like the letter the word A and then the pronoun I and so on.
So when I see things like that, I make sure to fix them.
When I'm going through and anonymizing, if there's a chunk that I cannot figure out what it was supposed to mean or replace it with the word illegible and so on.
So that's the the second pass through the transcript.
First pass is live, second pass is when I'm going through anonymize it.
I then send that to the participant that created the transcript with me and they give me a thumbs up.
If or they have a chance for a thumbs up for correcting any anonymization.
I'm not offering it to them to add any more feedback or to clarify any points.

If they offer that, I'll accept it, but I'm offering as like hey, just so you know, this is the actual document that will be quoted from please, you know, put your eyes on it for the sake of making sure that it's anonymized and isn't libelous or anything like that.
Then the the next layer of looking at the transcript and the third layer is what I'm actually going through and creating the table.
So I'll have here in my iMac which the monitor is big enough to do this.
On the right hand side I'll put the transcript and on the left hand side I'll put an empty dock and I'll create the same style of a three column table as I did back in 2020.
The first column just says hey, here's the time that this block begins at.
I've got this column that I'm calling summary, which is jottings about what's happening during that time block.
I find myself compared to 2020.
So in 2020 I would listen to it and kind of jot down my jottings about what I'm hearing and having to hear.
OK, I think we're changing topics, whereas in here I can kind of read through minutes on a time of a transcript and go, OK, here I can go do some jottings that cover what I've just read.
And here's where a break in kind of topic is For the first two transcripts, I experimented with going down the left column.
So doing a cell of jottings and then or going down the whole thing, doing a cell of jottings and doing what I call my code column where I'm spelling out more substantively.
Here's what I'm hearing, here's why it matters.
Kind of move up from literally they said this towards something that's more of substance for the the research topic.
And I'd do a jotting cell, I would do a code cell, do a jotting cell, I'd do a code cell.
I went down like that.
The most recent two interviews, I found it much quicker and still of good quality to go down the first column all the way to the bottom.
So I'd be doing the jottings for the whole thing and breaking it up in the chunks and then going into the right column and actually working my way back up.
And what this let me do is note and see these connections across a whole interview.
So when I see an idea that is emerging not within one chunk of the interview, but something that's emerging through connections throughout the interview.
Possibly because they keep bringing up a topic, possibly because I followed up on it, Possibly because the questions asked them to think about something multiple times in different ways.
I can get those ideas to come up and more explicitly link them with my annotations, my square bracket annotations, which are my researcher notes, and so on.

In other fields, non AI fields you might or the the belief is that you might see some pattern of industry advancing research on something and academia advancing the research on something I mean and then industry kind of picking it up and tweaking it for maybe some applied case or someone working together in that way.
But here we have industry and AI being the one who makes huge leaps and the advancement of AI research much more in some areas than academia does, and we get kind of looks a little different.

And you've got this interplay between industry and open source, between whether the power and the future of big models or powerful models is going to be more isolated to a few that have power or more dispersed.
So if open source can get a better foot in the door, that also makes more of a foot in door for academia as well to do things.

Because getting us writing is the important part so that we can then get our our thinking down and so on.

So another part is speaking about our I kind of going back to that idea of metaphors and ways that we come to understand and and view what we're working on.
Maybe these abstract things is doing it in a way that also lets us translate and speak to leadership, right?

And those don't have to be the exact same frames, but they should I hopefully like, work together, that we can work with our peers on something and maybe bring in people that we're speaking to and so on.

Since then was this sense of wanting to do things to maybe launder one's agency or so on, but being kind of tempted into using the AI to kind of cheat at things, to take shortcuts and stuff like that.

And there seems to be this relationship between this temptation to use AI for maybe more than we initially wanted to, or claim to be using it for, and so on seems to be a relationship between that temptation and this metaphor that keeps coming up of viewing AI as somehow more human than it is, right?
I keep thinking of Laura Hoffman's talk that she gave a while back where she showed a bunch of screenshots of previous, I think it was Harvard marketing around AI.
And it was so strange seeing the amount of kind of parental imagery and speak about AI, right?
They literally had this backsplash image on a web page that was about AI that had a father and a son, right?
And so in this way, there's this metaphor about treating it as more human than it is, or the the how tricky it is now with conversational AI thoughts and so on to reason about what it's doing.
Because we keep kind of putting more human agency on it than it maybe deserves, viewing it as maybe thinking or operating in a way that it just isn't fair to the facts of the case.
One is kind of all three I think kind of add a little bit more to the lit review already have on social change in AI.
One is that we've made great leaps in the technology of AI.
This is kind of contrast that human metaphor problem viewing AI is more human than it is.
We've made big leaps in the development of AI by moving away from trying to model how we think humans reason and instead say, well here is what computers are really good at.
Here's some proofs that this can approximate different functions, and here's the data that we can kind of plug into this and train on, and so on.
But letting computers really do what computers are really good at and take that limit.
Instead of just saying here's how humans think through the problem, let's model that directly.
Something else that has made it easier for people to suddenly be much more involved in the development of AI systems.

Maybe not advancing AI research itself, but applying AI in new areas is that there is an increase in, there's a decrease in barriers to working with AI, there's an increase in tooling to work with AI, these tools are intuitive and so on, and so people need to know less and less and less coding or computer science skills or so on to do really neat things with AI, right?
There's a lot of talk right now around prompt engineering and so on.
That is a new kind of skill that is emerging for how we even frame what it means to work with these AIS in a way that's a bit more abstracted from just working with code and so on.
And so the tooling around AI has changed more recently, which has had a big impact on kind of a market on AI systems that embed AI in them.

The, the last kind of piece here is that throughout this kind of social change history of AI is that there's repeatedly been surprises and about so that there's repeatedly been surprises about what AI could actually achieve or so on.
Kind of the flip side of the skepticism is when it is good, it's good in surprising ways.
One of the interviewees has said you don't make money betting against AI and that what's on the horizon and what's on the future for AI is really unclear and hard to predict.

More recently, something I want to add to that is a more recent interview, I think was the third interview I was speaking about that unclear future, but not in the sense of we can't be aware of what's in the future or that we're not aware of it, that we're just unconscious to it.
And that framing seemed to be like something a little trickier that maybe, yeah, we might be aware or whatever, but we're not thinking deeply about things.
We aren't thinking clearly about those things in the future.
So there might be things, even with an unclear, surprising horizon, that we actually can predict well enough and begin to reason about.
But for one reason or another, our awareness of it is muddied or incomplete or deprioritized or so on.
And so I like that framing, even if that's not how the participant meant it, of thinking about it as a consciousness right around what the future might hold.
