[Non-traditional sense of career, fell into doing policy; all background information, no new substance toward findings]
[risk, previous one, language of higher ups]
[maybe something with risk vs rule?]
The policy and practice of AI ethics plays out differently in education, public, and private spheres.

The public sphere is bound more by rules than the private, which is bound more by reputation than the public; and the public sphere is focused on its assigned mission than research at universities, which is driven more by the changing direction of one’s field and one’s funding.
[Education, how it is governed, cite into EPS literature, briefly.]
Moreover, regulation plays out in different levels, forms, scales, and areas of the government.

“If you wanna go much, much larger and much more powerful, you'd have to do legislation, and that's where Congress has to step in and write these laws. And then it would come back to us. And then [the Office of Management and Budget] would look at the legislation and say, here's your way, here's how you actually do the thing that was written down. And so for us to think about the people that are doing these things, it's really important to make the distinction between the corporate side—the private sector and the federal sector—because what we have to do has already been laid out pretty well for us. Now, what companies have to do is, you know—and I say this like kind of a not great way—they have to think about what does it mean for them to be ethical and do they choose to do so? And I think, this is why you have a lot of regulators thinking about, like Congress, thinking about putting restrictions or laws on AI because there isn't other than like reputational harm.... We should be looking for the frameworks that already work, the regulations that already work that we've seen.”
[Above, unlike private companies,] government agencies are required by recent policy to report their use of AI technologies.
Initially, there was high variability in how agencies fulfilled these mandates.
There have been recent efforts to refine those reporting requirements, and there is a public-facing database (with larger, internal-facing counterpart) bringing together these varied reports

Broadly, the newer requirements ask agencies to document their rights-impacting and safety-impacting uses of AI, as well as what additional steps they’ve taken in regards to those real or potential impacts

[This section does not seem to provide any new substance. I already have US vs. Non-US policy covered, well enough, in ch 2. The points in the slide they provided may be worth adding into the lit review, but what that adds, I feel, does not advance the substance of the dissertation.]
[Below, those who think most deeply are those who built a model, should document their thinking, institutional knowledge is important.]
Those designing a system for the first time can make great strides relying on best practices, guidelines, and literature of those who have written about AI Ethics before them

The NIST Risk Management Framework is a cut above most other starting points, one participant believes, as it is thorough and breaks down clearly one’s concerns into rights-impacting and safety-impacting aspects
[Documentation should involve model cards, cite into the model card paper(s)].
However, the language of “model card” may be misleading to practitioners—one participant recommends “systems card” as an alternative

In their experience working with vendors, the term “model card” has led practitioners to document only the original model’s features, falling short of documenting their thinking on how the system around their finetuned version of the model relates to specific business needs, presents new shortcomings, and so on
Moreover, these system cards are a place for a company to acknowledge where a system has bias, and where those biases are within bounds that the company is willing to accept the risk of
One can be considered, in some sense, a “good developer” by being good in their job, by also following moral practices, but not by being good in the moral sense alone

“I think being an engineer requires, should require, the morality piece, but it's not [just the morality piece]—you could be very moral about all these things and read up all the ethics and not be able to train anything.”

Getting at the moral sense of good involves following morally relevant best practices, which are often practices carried out at the organization level—either do things morally well yourself, or hire those who will and structure priorities and activities to support them

Getting at the moral sense of good also involves, at the individual level, relying on the morally relevant institutional knowledge of those who came before you, and taking strides to inform yourself of that prior knowledge
[Those who think most deeply about these things are those that built it first, below.]
Good in the skill sense involves staying up to date on the advancements and practices of the profession
Evidence of one’s continual learning is a strong indicator to companies that one will be a skillful engineer
Where one is good in the overlap of both senses can present itself in different ways
On the one hand, one’s ethical concerns may be the basis for taking certain action, such as aspiration toward the mission of one’s employer
On the other hand, one’s ethical concerns may constrain one’s action, either prescriptively or through principlist reasoning, such as IRB’s role in the protecting research subjects’ rights and safety

Which presentation one sees of the overlap of the two senses of good depends, at least in part, on the employment context: different business aims may make for different aspirations, different business practices may make for different considerations and constraints, and different business hiring may make for a team with different dispositions in the overlap of the two senses of good
[Time and priorities getting in the way of getting at those aspirations, previous interviews]
The participant sees their trajectory as the sum of a series of small side projects
[Hands on being a way to become aware of moral things you couldn’t have otherwise, below.]
They were aware that there were AI ethics questions in, say, robotics, but those sort of questions were outside of their field
Like others around them, the AI models they were working on were not rights or safety impacting
They hadn’t thought deeply about AI ethics until AI advanced enough that easily-accessible models could readily reflect moral concerns

“Most of us are big nerds at a bench and we're trying to solve our scientific thing, right? What changed, I think was the volume of data and the types of models that came out—like recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks and really transformers and maybe even embedding models. So, like word2vec really enabled us to take advantage of large-scale bits of data all at once and have I'm going to go out on a limb here and say that like word2vec is a large pre trained model. I know it'd be silly by today's standards to call it that, but it was revolutionary when it did, and when this thing came out really was the first time I thought about ethics and AI...That's when I was like—I discovered a lot of the research that came out from that. One of my favorite papers is [Bolukbasi et al 2016, Man is to computer programmer as woman is to homemaker]. I think it's a paper that codified that—...I was like super interested in this and I think I still have some apps that were up that really looked at the word embeddings, the King, the Queen, you know, the gender direction in word2vec models, and that's so fascinating and whether or not we could do a lot of this other stuff—, but I like really dove into this piece as much as possible, but I didn't start thinking about it until I had models that could reflect this.”

Policy can take place at the public level, imposed on companies from governments, and it can take place within companies themselves through self-regulation; and policy involves written rules and guidelines, on-the-ground practice [and norms, Lessig], [and socio-technical infrastructures, Lessig]
While practitioners believe that markets and the economy have great force in shaping the future of AI and AI ethics [all previous interviews], policy in all its senses also plays a substantive role

When bad AI ethics cases happen, the effect of these cases on downstream policy changes depends, in part, on the nature of the case: failures at the individual level, where an individual broke an existing policy, may be less impactful downstream than failures at an institutional level, where the outcome goes against our moral intuitions yet was not covered by existing policy
In either sort of case, what is salient is that an individual, or group, carried out an action where they should have known better not to, in one sense of “should morally know” or another

Educators should have students building models and detecting bias and other things of AI ethics concern; this will help them gain a deeper understanding, reflect on their understanding, and synthesize and test their ideas
[Being hands on makes you aware of ethical issues you wouldn’t have been aware of otherwise, below.]
The particular AI technology changes every year; but the pedagogy on preparing good future practitioners can be for the most part stable

The practitioners who design a system for the first time, or significantly scale it up, are the ones who will think most deeply about its edge cases, uses cases, ethical issues, and how it meets business needs
Future practitioners maintaining these systems will not have the time to think about it as deeply—nor should there be an expectation that they do
Those who know it the best, the original practitioners, should document the contours of the system well, providing in-depth and summary documentation
Future practitioners may, and should, rely on this deep thought that came before them
[Those that built the system will be aware of ethical issues that they could only have to come to an awareness of by building the system, below.]

“When you work on a project, right, like, so—AI ethics as a field is very broad. It like, it cannot anticipate all the different use cases, so it has to come up with guidelines and rules and use cases of things that's happened before. Like, we have observed this, and so we're gonna synthesize all of these things into best practices or in terms of, like, the people who are like the engineering things is like, here's how you can bias a word embedding. Cool. That's how they like think of these things. 






“But if you're a practitioner, if like you're building your AI system, you're like...you're taking a pre trained model and you're fine tuning it. For example, you have a specific business need and you have a couple months to deeply think about how to, one, solve your business need and if you're a good ethicist to think about what sort of harms it can cause. You understand the use case so intimately, because that's all you've been doing, right? You will probably be the person who thinks—you and your team will probably be the ones who think about this problem more than anybody else will ever do it ever again in the history of this project, unless it's deployed to a larger scale than it was before, but typically things are not. They're like, you build a thing and it grows a little bit, you know, no more than ten times its size. And then it sits there and it's maintained. 




“And what happens is that the people that maintain it are often not the people who are in the initial room, who are building it. And so that institutional knowledge for people had the discussions needs to be documented somewhere, because nobody wants to read, you know, an 80-page report on why this thing is gonna happen. It's not gonna work. But what they do need to do, it’s been, a 2-page report about ‘do not use it like this’ and then you're like, ‘wait, why?,’ and then maybe that's where the 80-page report is important because you do care about it, but you need, you know, ‘here be dragons’ on your model to know that there are specific things that you've seen because you can't anticipate all risks, but you're when you're often working with this, you find out the risks. 




“And a lot of the risks have nothing to do with the ethics. A lot of the risks have to do with data quality. You feed it Unicode characters and your system expects ASCII characters, you get garbage. That should fall into the—that is so good for an engineer to know because you're like oh, everything's Unicode now and you're working with this legacy system, that sort of thought process should be put into the ethics process. now, like the example of language that we talked about earlier. You might not a priori have the time to think about [every possible problem]. Nor should you. Your job is to maintain. You should have relied on the past groups to do all the work for that.”
Students and practitioners come to an awareness of logistical and ethical issues in AI when building these systems themselves first hand
This awareness is deeper than if they hadn’t built the system themselves; and they may become aware of things this way that they wouldn’t have if they hadn’t built the system themselves
So, for students and practitioners to develop and maintain their AI ethics senses, it is important for them to be continually building and learning through building
[Employers look to GitHub as evidence of continual learning, above]

Much AI Ethics literature that has pervaded academic discussion is or amounts to principlism: enumerates a number of morally relevant aims, grounds them in real understanding of the practice, and provide method for achieving and balancing between them.
This is a view from, “what do I do.”

column1: Non-isolation can involve individuals with a combination of technical and ethical skills; an interdisciplinary team working in close collaboration; and cross-functional but non-collaborative efforts, where technical work is checked by ethical assessments.
Moreover, collaborations can include employees on the same team; those within the same company; employees working alongside contractors; and employees connected to third party venders and tools.
[See Business Ethics literature on team construction?]

A business may use a number of these organizational strategies at once, depending on a range of factors; this includes (inter alia) pressures, needs, and capabilities to assess certain facets of ethical AI more or less than others.
[Read more about FRCA and Dodd Frank, data privacy, in frame of data infra]

AI Ethics is no longer hypothetical in the discourse, confined to special research and science fiction; it has made it into the mainstream. [Insert string of examples, like from daily news, honestly citing that AI tools for babycare wouldn’t be a bad idea.]

While this has certainly had the effect of broadening the audience for AI Ethics, it may also lead practitioners to AI Ethics fatigue; as one participant put it, “I'm happy to hear about Taylor Swift some more like, right? [This was when Taylor Swift’s attendance at Travis Kelce’s football games was pop news.] Can you hear some more about Taylor Swift? I'm so tired of hearing about Sam Altman.”

While [most/some] participants remarked having a non-traditional or meandering trajectory getting into AI Ethics, some (as they saw their trajectories) knew at a young age what they wanted to do, felt able to achieve those dreams in light of their role models, and arrived at AI Ethics through a natural progression of interests and callings.

“I I decided a long time ago I wanted to be an attorney. I was seven, and Sandra Day O'Connor had just been named to the bench. So that was a little influential to say, ‘You know, there's a woman on the bench now, you can do anything you want.’ … I got into law that way. Before I went to law school though, I was an undergraduate...and I worked at a lobbying law firm because I wanted to know how that works. So I worked at the intersection of money and the law and figured out how that works before I went to law school, so that when I was done, I would be able to be more effective. And what I was doing was working with consumer rights, which I added privacy later because all of my years in consumer rights. I realized that all we are is data, and if we don't have any agency over that data, then we don't really have any more rights.”
[New protocol question? Do you feel like you needed role models or examples of others like you doing this work to get into AI Ethics to the extent you are now?]
Participants were divided on whether the AI industry would have its reckoning in the future.
[Other views that were pessimistic, and why.]

On the other hand, some spoke with an annoyed conviction that it was only a matter of time before today’s present concerns turned into industry regulation, to force businesses to align with a common sense of “good,” such as in the area of protecting consumer rights.

The form that this hypothetical future “regulation” will take, in any sense of regulation, and regardless of one’s pessimistic or optimistic stance, may run counter to the common view that the company is ultimately liable for AI harms.

A motivation for practitioners learning ethics skills, as one participant put it, is that liability may one day fall on the individual deemed responsible; exercising ethics skills may protect them by for example preventing harm and documenting due diligence.
[Vigilance connection]

As companies implement regulatory requirements more and more, the fear of individual liability may come to serve as a stick for learning ethics skills; the comparably lower pay (or lack of pay) for those who do AI Ethics work is a rotten carrot today.

At the same time, as companies implement regulatory requirements more and more, at least at first, one participants expects a period of “compliance washing,” specious practices that meet the surface letter but not the spirit of AI assessment reporting requirements.
[Connect to how this has played out in the gov’t too, has taken time to get there]
[Don’t make bad things in the first place; connect to goal-driven comments I’ve heard before]
[Do Business Ethics review connected to SDLCs?; connect to comments about perpetual beta, consumers taking the blunt]
The generation of students today does have thoughts about ethics.
[2020 comments about they do care about eg video game ethics – add 2020 study to methods]
They are already skeptical about large corporations and hold a belief about labor where they refuse to invest themselves too deeply in a company that does not care about them.
Instead, they are primed already to speak out, to blow whistles.
[Connect to what this feels like though, as students about to graduate, I will do evil for money, and Ullman scene with the keylogger]
[TODO, they continue talking about it in the next segment: the virtue idea, the inner instinct idea, aspirational agency]

column1: In most visions of the future, however unclear, the structure of participants’ imagined narratives was one of “come together, or go off the cliff,” so to say: that a future where AI issues were resolved was a future that followed an arrival at a shared vision, understanding, scope of acceptability, or compromise.

column1: Statements that the car would go “off the cliff” if we did not come to a shared vision—statements like this were not intended to be taken literally, but appeared to be expressions of apprehensive dissatisfaction, an exasperated sigh about the state of today’s disagreements around AI and how to get people to be “good” as they do it, a begrudging acceptance that a future where we all agree is never promised and that the exhausting conversations of today may never stop.

column1: On the one hand, participants frequently spoke about the outsized power of a small number of large companies; how stories of AI doom made these companies’ models seem all that more power, and therefore boosted their marketing potential; how companies have outsized power to not just drive markets, but also to shape narratives about AI Ethics itself and what AI ethicists look like; and how one’s realistic abilities to influence large companies is extremely limited.
